// Synchronous Execution	Asynchronous Execution
// Tasks execute one after another in sequence.	Tasks can start now and finish later without blocking other code.
// Each task waits for the previous task to complete.	Other tasks can continue while waiting for a task to complete.
// Blocking in nature.	Non-blocking in nature.
// Simpler and easier to understand.	More efficient for time-consuming operations.
// Can make the application slow if a task takes longer.	Improves performance and responsiveness.
// Execution follows a linear flow.	Execution flow may not be sequential.
// Used for simple operations that complete quickly.	Used for API calls, file operations, timers, and network requests.
// Example Flow

Synchronous

console.log("Task 1");
console.log("Task 2");
console.log("Task 3");



Asynchronous

console.log("Task 1");

setTimeout(() => {
    console.log("Task 2");
}, 2000);

console.log("Task 3");




//Key Points
// Synchronous = Execute tasks one by one, waiting for each to finish.
// Asynchronous = Start a task and continue executing other tasks without waiting.
// JavaScript is single-threaded, but it handles asynchronous operations using the Event Loop, Web APIs, and Callback Queue.
// Common asynchronous methods: setTimeout(), setInterval(), Promises, async/await, and API requests (fetch()).